    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Women, the Court and Our Votes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rod Mac Kenzie letter on May 16 editorial hails Supreme Court ruling overturning law to let women sue attackers in federal court</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Violence Against the Constitution'' (editorial, May 16): Hurray for the Supreme Court. The Constitution is a greater document than the political whims of the times.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Violence Against the Constitution'' (editorial, May 16): Hurray for the Supreme Court. The Constitution is a greater document than the political whims of the times.</p>
        <p>I am for the protection of women. I am not for overturning the right and ability of the states to protect those rights because some in Washington feel that the states are not fulfilling that function. I am for convincing the electorate that current laws do not adequately address violence between the sexes.</p>
        <p>The dialogue around the convincing might bring some perspective that violence is done by both sexes to each other. The excessive use of restraining orders and the inability of those orders to guarantee safety for those they seek to protect need a full airing. This dialogue will create a collective best solution rather than the father-in-Washington-knows-best solution offered by the Beltway.</p>
        <p>ROD MACKENZIE  Woodside, Calif., May 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
